LEVEL 1: Single-Row Subqueries (Basics)
1. Find all employees whose salary is greater than the average salary of the company.
2. Retrieve employees earning the minimum salary in the company.
3. List employees whose salary is equal to the maximum salary in the IT department.
4. Find departments where the average salary is higher than the overall company average.
5. Display employees hired after the earliest hire date in the company.

LEVEL 2: Multi-Row Subqueries (IN, ANY, ALL)
6. Find employees who work in departments located in India or the United States.
7. List employees whose salary is higher than ALL salaries of the HR department.
8. Find employees whose salary is greater than ANY salary in the Sales department.
9. Retrieve all products that have never been ordered.
10. Find customers who have placed more than one order.

LEVEL 3: EXISTS & Correlated Subqueries
11. List all departments that have at least one employee.
12. Find employees who earn more than the average salary of their own department.
13. Retrieve employees who do not belong to any department.
14. Find customers who have never placed an order using EXISTS.
15. Display products that are ordered by at least one customer from India.

LEVEL 4: Subqueries in SELECT & FROM
16. Display employee name, salary, and the average salary of their department.
17. Find departments where the number of employees is greater than 5
(using subquery in FROM).
18. Show job titles along with the highest salary for each job title.

LEVEL 5: CTEs (WITH Clause)
19. Using a CTE, find employees whose salary is above their departmentâ€™s average salary.
20. Create a CTE that calculates total sales per customer, then display customers whose total sales exceed â‚¹1,00,000.

